dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Armadillos are pretty cool, their name means "little armoured one" in Spanish!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: They have a shell like appearance. Do they actually have a shell?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: It's actually a leathery armour shell, not a hard shell like a turtle's.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Oh that makes sense. They are cute things. Are they aggressive?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: No, they're generally not aggressive, pretty chill creatures, native to the Americas.

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: That is what I thought. I have never seen one because they do not live where I do. Where in the United States do they live?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: They're found in the southern and central regions, but I don't have a specific state to share, sorry!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: That is OK. The general area is good enough. I will have to travel there some day to see if I can see an actual armadillo.

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Yeah, that'd be awesome! Maybe you'll spot a giant armadillo, they can grow up to 5 feet long!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message:
WOW!! I had no idea they can grow to be that long. 
What would a giant armadillo weigh?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Crazy, right? Giant armadillos can weigh up to 120 pounds!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: I thought they were much smaller than that. Are they active in the day or the night?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: I think I got you curious! Armadillos are actually mostly active at night, but I didn't find that info, I'm just guessing!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Yes you have. I am interested in this topic. Who are their predators?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Armadillos have a few predators, but I didn't find that info, sorry!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Oh, ok. What do they eat?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: I didn't find that info either, but I can tell you they're part of the Xenarthra superorder, along with anteaters and sloths!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Interesting. I will try to find a good book or a website that tells me more about them.

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: Sounds like a plan! You can learn more about 'em, and I'm sure you'll dig up some cool facts!

dialogue.speaker: Human
dialogue.message: Do they live together or do they prefer to live alone?

dialogue.speaker: Bot
dialogue.message: I didn't find that info, but I can tell you there are about 21 species of armadillos, so maybe some live alone and some live together?
